prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Our goal is to detect continuum emission at the same wavelength as that of the discovery observations, which corresponds to ALMA band 7. We will use a standard ``single continuum'' at 344GHz (i.e. 4x128 dual-polarisation channels over a 7.5-GHz usable bandwidth). Our science goals rely on continuum detections and, we do not a-priori know the frequencies of any strong emission lines in this band, so for simplicity we use a single frequency for all sources. Although note that the spectral resolution of 31.25MHz, which corresponds to around 28km/s, is sufficient to resolve the expected serendipitous z = 4-5 [CII] line detections (FWHM ~ 300km/s; Swinbank et al. 2012). Our sources are weak enough that phase referencing is necessary, but we leave the choice of phase calibrator to the project, to be decided at runtime along with the other standard calibrators (flux, bandpass, etc.).

We will observe the submm sources in Band 7 (345GHz) in the C36-1 configuration, resulting in a resolution of 1" (~8kpc at z ~ 2). This is similar to the likely rest-frame ~250um extent of the SMGs contributing to these sources (e.g. Simpson et al. 2015) and thus optimal for their detection. The primary beam is 18" which is more than sufficient to encompass all the SMGs contributing to the submm emission, even in the blended situations. Critically, the observing frequency is the same as the S2CLS discovery map and thus the comparison between the fluxes straightforward. This will allow the identification of submm sources with missing flux in the ALMA maps due to large numbers of faint SMGs or very extended submm emission in some SMGs, <~7" (50 kpc), either due to multiple clumps or diffuse cirrus-like emission (c.f. Stevens et al. 2003; Hayward et al. 2011).

We propose 850um mapping with ALMA of complete sample of SCUBA-2 detected SMGs in the equatorial UDS field. This map reaches 1 sigma = 0.9 mJy over one square degree (Fig. 1), detecting 533 sources above 4 sigma. This corresponds to an apparent flux of 3.6 mJy. This is the largest survey of bright sources from the well-studied 850um population in any ALMA-visible field and it comes with a wealth of archival data, including some of the deepest near-infrared imaging, as well as deep Herschel PACS/SPIRE observations. Twenty six of these sources were observed by Simpson et al. (2015) as part of a Cycle-1 program and we therefore remove these, leaving a total of 507 submm sources to be observed in Cycle 3. Our sources cover a range of deboosted 850um fluxes of 3-14mJy. Based on our experience from Cycle 0 and Cycle 1, we have adopted 0.25mJy as our sensitivity goal which is the same as our Cycle-1 program and a sufficient depth to uncover >1mJy SMGs if the sources break up into multiple components (Simpson et al. 2015). According to the ALMA Sensitivity Calculator, this depth takes about 42 seconds per map. This will yield a 12sigma detection of the faintest SMGs if unblended and would still recover all of the flux for the >6mJy sources at >5 sigma, even if they comprise 3--5 sub-components spread out to the edge of the primary beam (due to blending and/or lensing; Fig.~1). For our complete sample of 507 SMGs, the total observing time including overheads would be 11.1 hours.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
We propose ALMA band-7 continuum follow-up observations of an uniformly selected sample of 533 submillimeter sources with S850 > 3.5mJy from our SCUBA-2 survey of the UKIDSS-UDS. We expect to precisely locate almost 1000 SMGs with S850 > 1mJy. With this unprecedented large number of SMGs with precise positions, our science goals are to 1) measure the angular correlation function and so derive the halo mass, building the evolutionary links between SMGs and other high-z galaxy populations and their local desendants, 2) test whether brighter SMGs are more likely to break up into multiple faint components, and derive intrinsic number counts, 3) precisely identify the counterparts in other wavelengths and so derive redshift distributions, in particular the form of the high-z tail.
With a sample of ~1000 ALMA SMGs (~10 times larger than that of previously samples such as ALESS), we will measure the multi-wavelength properties of the population, redshift distribution and most critically their clustering, allowing us to properly link SMGs with their proposed descendants: luminous ellipticals.
